  1. Load in the libraries you need, and look at the backpack data. Take note of variable names and dimensions.
  1. What is the distribution of backpack weights that students are carrying? Choose an appropriate graph to show the distribution.
backpack %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = backpack_weight) +
  geom_histogram(colour = "white") +
  labs(x = "Backpack Weight (kg)",
       y = "Count",
       title = "Distribution of Backpack Weight")

  • This shows that the majority of backpack weights are around 10kg.
  1. Are there differences in backpack weight between sex?
backpack %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = backpack_weight, fill = sex) +
  geom_histogram(position = "dodge", binwidth = 1) +
  labs(x = "Backpack Weight (kg)",
       y = "Count",
       title = "Distribution of Backpack Weight",
       fill = "Sex")

  • This shows that males carry slightly heavier backpacks than females.
  1. What is the relationship between body weight and backpack weight?
backpack %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = body_weight, y = backpack_weight) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = lm,
              se = FALSE) +
  labs(x = "Body Weight",
       y = "Backpack Weight",
       title = "Relationship between Backpack and Body Weight")

NA
  • This scatter plot shows a correlation between body weight and backpack weight.
  1. Is this relationship different between men and women? Choose an appropriate plot and interpret your findings.
backpack %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = body_weight, y = backpack_weight) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = lm,
              se = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~ sex) +
  labs(x = "Body Weight",
       y = "Backpack Weight",
       title = "Relationship Between Backpack and Body Weight")

  • Initially these plots show that there is a stronger correlation between body weight and backpack weight in females than in males. But if I change the limits to show the majority of people from each sex, with no extremes, it shows a very similar correlation. Meaning that the sex doesnt matter too much, its more the body_weight.
backpack %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = body_weight, y = backpack_weight) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = lm,
              se = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~ sex) +
    scale_y_continuous(expand = c(0,0),
                     limits = c(0, 30)) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(100, 200)) +
  labs(x = "Body Weight",
       y = "Backpack Weight",
       title = "Relationship Between Backpack and Body Weight")

  1. What proportion of students report back pain?
back_pain_prop <- backpack %>% 
  summarise(back_p_prop = sum(back_problems) / n())
back_pain_prop

back_pain <- backpack %>% 
  mutate(back_problems = case_when(
    back_problems == 1 ~ "Yes",
    back_problems == 0 ~ "No"))

back_pain %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = back_problems) +
  geom_bar() +
  labs(x = "Back Problems",
       y = "Count",
       fill = NULL)

  • This shows that around 1/3 of students reported back pain
  1. Is this proportion different between men and women?
back_pain <- backpack %>% 
  mutate(back_problems = case_when(
    back_problems == 1 ~ "Yes",
    back_problems == 0 ~ "No"))
    
back_pain %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = back_problems, fill = sex) +
  geom_bar(position = "fill") +
  labs(x = "Back Problems",
       y = "Count",
       title = "Proportion of Students with Back Problems",
       fill = NULL)

  • This shows that a higher proportion of females have reported back problems.
  1. Now youve investigated your data separately, create plots to describe the relationship between backpack weight, body weight, gender and reported backpain.
back_pain %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = body_weight, y = backpack_weight, colour = sex) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap( ~ back_problems) +
  labs(x = "Body Weight",
       y = "Backpack Weight",
       fill = NULL,
       title = "Relationship Between Backpack Weight and Body Weight")

  • This shows that the majority of people reporting back pain are females in the 100 - 150kg weight range.
